article.description: Ann Wauters had a career-high 24 points and nine rebounds, leading the New York Liberty to a 67-53 victory over the Indiana Fever on Sunday.
article.headline: Liberty go 10-for-10 from the line to close out game
article.linkText: Liberty chill Fever behind Wauters' career-high 24 points
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- After a slow start, the New York Liberty went to
a zone defense early in the second half and it paid off.

Ann Wauters had a career-high 24 points and nine rebounds,
leading the Liberty to a 67-53 victory over the Indiana Fever on
Sunday.

Elena Baranova and Shameka Christon scored 14 points apiece, and
Becky Hammon added 11 to help the Liberty (12-11) win for the
fourth time in six games.

"Whether it's junk, zone, man ... if it helps us win, I'll play
it as much as we can," New York coach Pat Coyle said. "If we can
just play them zone and not give them second shots. We gave them
too many in the first half, but in the second half we did a better
job."

Wauters shot 9-for-12 from the field and eclipsed her previous
scoring high of 23, set against Connecticut on July 7.

Natalie Williams had a season-high 15 points, and Tamika
Catchings added 10 points and 10 rebounds for her 35th career
double-double to lead the Fever (14-9).

New York, which squandered double-digit halftime leads in losses
to Houston and Connecticut in its last two games, started off
sloppy against Indiana. The Liberty, averaging 14.1 turnovers per
game, committed five in the first five minutes and 11 in the first
half.

The Fever also had nine of their 13 offensive rebounds in the
opening period.

"In the first half, we weren't always ready," Wauters said.
"We could have picked up our intensity. They had some easy
rebounds, and that was killing us. They got more chances and more
chances."

After Williams' jumper 15 seconds into the second half increased
Indiana's lead to 30-23, New York scored seven straight points to
tie it for the first time since it was 2-2.

Williams stretched Indiana's lead to 36-33 with a reverse layup.

"My role is to come out and be more aggressive," Williams
said. "I could tell we needed some scoring inside, but obviously
it wasn't enough."

The Liberty then went on a 14-0 run, capped by Christon's
jumper, to take an 11-point lead with 9:33 remaining.

"After halftime we came with more intensity, more energy, and
that run really helped us," Wauters said.

Rookie Tan White scored eight straight points for the Fever with
a pair of 3-pointers and a driving layup to cut the deficit to
52-48 four minutes later.

Christon's 3 gave New York a seven-point lead with 4:40 left.
Hammon made a driving layup and a pair of free throws to push the
advantage to 59-49 with 1:56 remaining.

"The Liberty have more size, with Baranova, Wauters and
Christon," Catchings said. "Between those three, they can pretty
much switch everything because they all play the 3, 4, and 5."

New York, the WNBA's top free throw shooting team, went
10-for-10 from the line over the final two minutes to seal the win.

After going 0-for-4 on 3s in the first half, the Liberty went
5-for-11 after the break. They finished with 16 turnovers, and
outrebounded the Fever 30-28.

"We couldn't hit any outside shots and we turned it over too
much," Williams said. "We've been struggling in the offensive
area, and New York just hit some great shots. We allowed them to
hit too many 3s in the second half and that's what hurt us."

Indiana went ahead in the first half, using a 7-0 run -- capped
by Catchings' steal and fastbreak layup -- to take a 13-4 lead with
15:23 left.

The Liberty climbed back with a 6-0 run, with Wauters accounting
for all the scoring, to pull within 15-14 with just over 11 minutes
remaining. Williams' layup seven minutes later capped an 8-2 run
that pushed Indiana's lead to 25-17, and the Fever led 28-23 at the
break.

Baranova, who also had eight rebounds, hit a pair of free throws
5½ minutes in to reach 2,000 points for her career.

Crystal Robinson missed her second straight game for New York
due to an injured right pinkie. Christon started in her place
again.
